# hilavitkutin-api shame

Known gaps with explanations. Each `## <key>` header silences the
matching lint violation keyed by `<key>`.

## KitDispatch

`KitDispatch<K>` is named in `DESIGN.md.tmpl` as one of the four
`Dispatch` routers exported by the `Provider` substrate, but the
struct itself lives in `hilavitkutin-kit` next to the `Kit` trait.
The api crate cannot depend on the kit crate (the layering is
api → kit, not kit → api), and `KitDispatch`'s `Dispatch` impl
needs to read `K::Units` and `K::Owned` to compute the next
typestate accumulator. Both associated types come from the `Kit`
trait, which only exists in the kit crate. Moving `Kit` into api
would invert the layering for one trait that is already kept
deliberately separate (it depends on api primitives plus a small
declarative shape; consumers reach for kit when they want the
preset bundle, not when they want the api). The cleaner answer is
to keep `Kit` and `KitDispatch` co-located in the kit crate and
let the api `Dispatch` trait declaration name the four router
shapes by convention. Decision recorded in
`mock/research/notes/202605091700_src_apply_decisions.md` (D7).

Consumers reach `KitDispatch` via `hilavitkutin_kit::KitDispatch`.
The api-side `DESIGN.md.tmpl` mention is a forward reference to
the kit crate's surface, equivalent to how the api `WorkUnit`
trait references `Always` / `On<V>` schedule markers from the
work_unit module without the markers needing to live in a separate
location.
